RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is an architecture that combines information retrieval with generative models to produce more accurate and grounded responses. It addresses the limits of models that rely only on training data by dynamically retrieving relevant information from external sources at query time. The workflow involves indexing documents, splitting text into chunks, creating embeddings, and storing them in a vector database (e.g., Chroma or Pinecone); a user query is embedded and used to retrieve relevant chunks that guide generation. Building an effective pipeline requires tuning chunk size, overlap, embedding model selection, and retrieval strategy. Advanced techniques include reranking, hybrid search (keyword + vector), and context compression to improve relevance and efficiency.
